<subSubSection pageId="60" pageNumber="687" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="60.[716,1305,481,908]" lastBlockId="60.[92,1301,914,3312]" pageId="60" pageNumber="687">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1907" box="[719,868,600,633]" class="Mammalia" family="Cercopithecidae" genus="Cercopithecus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="60" pageNumber="687" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hamlyni">C. hamlyni</taxonomicName>
is placed in its own species group. Lowland and highland forms of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1907" box="[719,865,679,712]" class="Mammalia" family="Cercopithecidae" genus="Cercopithecus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="60" pageNumber="687" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hamlyni">C. hamlyni</taxonomicName>
differ in cranial morphology and are classified as subspecies: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Pocock" authorityYear="1907" box="[1201,1304,717,750]" class="Mammalia" family="Cercopithecidae" genus="Cercopithecus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Primates" pageId="60" pageNumber="687" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hamlyni">hamlyni</taxonomicName>
and kahuziensis. In their 2003 review of the taxonomy of the African primates, P. Grubb and colleagues acknowledged doubts expressed by J. Hart concerning the validity of kahuziensis and indicated the need for further study. Two subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
